<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF107-970-892  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 970 892.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Communications News  Dec 1989 v26 n12 p22(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Fiber LANs: FDDI makes local-area networking even more intriguing.andO;(Fiber Distributed Data Interface)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Fiber Distributed Data Interface (FDDI) standards now beingfinalized for high-performance fiber-optic LANs will allow datatransmission rates of 100M-bps while accommodating real-time datacommunications.andP;  Fiber-optic technology provides a broaderbandwidth and greater immunity to noise than current cable-basednetworks; it also has low signal degradation, is flexible and easyto upgrade, is lighter and smaller, and is free of troublesomeground loops.andP;  FDDI LANs will connect mainframes and peripheralsand will serve as backbones for multiple lower-speed LANs foroffice automation, factory automation, computer-aided engineeringand other applications.andP;  The networks will support 500workstations up to two kilometers apart, will use 1,300-nanometerwavelength to optimize fiber bandwidth and will require no specialrepeaters, amplifiers or other signal-conditioning equipment.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Fiber OpticsData CommunicationsLocal Area NetworksInterfaceStandardsGovernment RegulationFiber Distributed Data Interface StandardBroadband.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>